[106]\~ \~ \~ \~  We should of course add that the question of excessive pricing \'96 or, at least, the possibility of challenging pricing conduct \'96 is unlikely to arise in the case of a legal monopoly precisely because, in the current economic policy environment, such an institution will, invariably, be subject to regulation. }{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
As already noted, it is our view that Section 8(a) is precisely intended to apply to those rare markets that are }{\i\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
uncontested}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
 (monopolised or \'91super-dominated\'92), }{\i\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
incontestable}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
 (subject to insurmountable entry barriers) and }{\i\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
unregulated}{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
 (not subject to price regulation).}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs20\loch\f3
\~  The South African market for flat steel products is, the evidence shows, just such a market, and this is why the proposal of Evans and Padilla and other writers that the powers of competition authorities to intervene in pricing conduct be reserved for the most exceptional circumstances is, in our view, strictly adhered to in this decision even though we do not require it to be restricted to a case of a legal monopoly.}
