It seems to follow that, in determining the economic value of a good or service, the cost savings to the firm resulting from the subsidised loan or the lower than market rental \'96 or indeed any other special advantage, current or historical, that serves to reduce the particular firm\'92s costs below the notional competitive norm ought to be disregarded. Thus economic value\'92 is a notional objective competitive-market standard, and not one derived from circumstances peculiar to the particular firm. If the firm\'92s price is no higher than economic value, no contravention of s 8(a) can arise. If, however, the firm\'92s price is in fact higher than economic value so determined, the test of reasonableness in respect of the difference remains to be applied. The expression \'91reasonable profit\'92}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#_ftn71" }{\fldrslt \cf2\ul\ulc0\langfe255\lang255\lang255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs26\lang7177\loch\f6
[71]}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
}} }{\b\rtlch \ltrch\loch\lang7177\loch\f3
when dealing with economic value should be avoided. The test of reasonableness applies to the excess of price over economic value, and thus only to the element of \'91pure profit\'92 (over and above \'91normal profit\'92) implicit in that price.\~  It is at this stage of the enquiry that\~  circumstances peculiar to the particular dominant firm would rationally come into the reckoning. It would seem sound, when considering whether the higher price bears a reasonable relation to economic value or not, to take into account the benefits flowing to the firm from the subsidised loan, long-term low rental, or other special advantage which may serve to reduce its own long-run average costs below the notional norm. Having regard to all the particular circumstances, it might then be concluded that no addition of \'91pure\'92 or \'91economic\'92 profit by means of a price higher than economic value could reasonably be justified, or that the extent of the excess which might otherwise be justified would fall to be reduced. By parity of reasoning, accounting costs may reflect an uncompetitive inefficiency. The criterion of economic value, on the other hand, recognises only the costs that would be recovered in long-run competitive equilibrium. Accordingly, it is possible that a dominant firm\'92s price may be substantially and also unreasonably higher than economic value even when the accounting profit of the firm reveals no such picture.}{{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#_ftn72" }{\fldrslt \cf2\ul\ulc0\langfe255\lang255\lang255\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs26\lang7177\loch\f6
[72]}}}
